LUATING BIBLIOGRAPHIC EDUCATION' A REVIEW AND CRITIQUE.     CONTRIBUTION TO A THEMATIC ISSUE ON LIBRARY USE INSTRUCTION. DISCUSSES SOMEREASONS FOR EVALUATING BIBLIOGRAPHIC INSTRUCTION PROGRAMMES. DESCRIBES THE USEOF THE TEST, THE SURVEY, AND ILLUMINATIVE EVALUATION AS METHODS OF EVALUATIONBY VARIOUS US AND EUROPEAN EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTIONS. CONSIDERS THE STATISTICALAND OTHER PROBLEMS INVOLVED WITH THESE TECHNIQUES, AND ARGUES THAT NONE OFTHEM ARE COMPLETELY SATISFACTORY, AND THAT IT MAY BE SOME TIME BEFORE TESTINGPROCEDURES CATCH UP WITH USER INSTRUCTION PROGRAMMES